docs.abstract: The consultant, which said it would cease most operations in the United States and Britain, relied on Facebook data to profile and target voters during the 2016 campaign.
docs.snippet: The consultant, which said it would cease most operations in the United States and Britain, relied on Facebook data to profile and target voters during the 2016 campaign.
docs.lead_paragraph: The embattled political consulting firm Cambridge Analytica announced on Wednesday that it would cease most operations and file for bankruptcy amid growing legal and political scrutiny of its business practices and work for Donald J. Trump’s presidential campaign.

headline.main: Cambridge Analytica to File for Bankruptcy After Misuse of Facebook Data
headline.print_headline: Scandal Sinks Firm That Mined Facebook to Target U.S. Voters

byline.original: By Nicholas Confessore and Matthew Rosenberg

docs.abstract: The company’s stock has declined precipitously since hitting its peak in early February, battered by disclosures about improper use of its data.
docs.snippet: The company’s stock has declined precipitously since hitting its peak in early February, battered by disclosures about improper use of its data.
docs.lead_paragraph: Over the last half decade, few stocks have been more beloved by investors and Wall Street analysts than Facebook. No wonder: After a rocky initial public offering in 2012, it has rolled over one obstacle after another, including the shift to mobile computing and the rise of photo sharing. It delivered revenue and user growth that surpassed even the most optimistic projections.

headline.main: Facebook Falls From Grace, and Investors’ Stock Holdings Tumble Too
headline.print_headline: As Facebook Loses Luster, Tech Stocks Await Fallout

docs.abstract: After a meeting at the New York attorney general’s office on Thursday, an investor group agreed to buy part of the beleaguered entertainment studio’s assets.
docs.snippet: After a meeting at the New York attorney general’s office on Thursday, an investor group agreed to buy part of the beleaguered entertainment studio’s assets.
docs.lead_paragraph: LOS ANGELES — In a surprise twist in the continuing saga of the Weinstein Company, an investor group said on Thursday that it had reached an agreement to buy most of the assets of the near-bankrupt studio, just days after a deal had been declared all but dead.

headline.main: Deal for Weinstein Co., Seemingly Dead, Is Reached
headline.print_headline: New Life For Deal To Acquire Weinstein

docs.abstract: Legislation would allow more home building along transit routes to reduce gas-guzzling commutes. Some who support the goal have denounced the method.
docs.snippet: Legislation would allow more home building along transit routes to reduce gas-guzzling commutes. Some who support the goal have denounced the method.
docs.lead_paragraph: SAN FRANCISCO — It’s an audacious proposal to get Californians out of their cars: a bill in the State Legislature that would allow eight-story buildings near major transit stops, even if local communities object.

headline.main: A Bold, Divisive Plan to Wean Californians From Cars
headline.print_headline: In California, a Green Split Over a Density Push

byline.original: By Conor Dougherty and Brad Plumer

docs.abstract: Propel was begun to bring convenience and new services to food stamp recipients. A big government contractor is getting in the way.
docs.snippet: Propel was begun to bring convenience and new services to food stamp recipients. A big government contractor is getting in the way.
docs.lead_paragraph: Four years ago, Jimmy Chen left a lucrative perch as a product manager at Facebook to found Propel, what he calls an “anti-poverty software company.”

headline.main: This Start-Up Says It Wants to Fight Poverty. A Food Stamp Giant Is Blocking It.
headline.print_headline: Food Stamps App Is Handy, And in Many Places Blocked

docs.abstract: As one horse farm owner put it, the high costs of breeding horses can lead to big payoffs, or nothing at all.
docs.snippet: As one horse farm owner put it, the high costs of breeding horses can lead to big payoffs, or nothing at all.
docs.lead_paragraph: Whoever owns the horse that wins the Kentucky Derby knows one bet will pay off: The breeding fees for that champion colt will dwarf what he has earned on the racetrack.

headline.main: Forget the Kentucky Derby Prize. The Big Return on Investment Is in Breeding.
headline.print_headline: Forget the Kentucky Derby Prize. Breeding Will Generate a Lot More.

docs.abstract: Shareholders opposing the company’s merger with its Japanese partner have appointed a new chief executive and board as they look to change or derail the deal.
docs.snippet: Shareholders opposing the company’s merger with its Japanese partner have appointed a new chief executive and board as they look to change or derail the deal.
docs.lead_paragraph: Xerox’s plan to merge its business with Fujifilm of Japan looks to be increasingly in jeopardy, as its chairman, its chief executive and a majority of its board members said they would resign in favor of a slate of new leaders favored by shareholders opposing the deal.

headline.main: Xerox’s Leaders Depart, Putting Fujifilm Deal in Jeopardy
headline.print_headline: Xerox Shuffle Puts Merger In Jeopardy

docs.abstract: A report sent to Parliament said there was evidence to suggest that Novartis made payments to politicians.
docs.snippet: A report sent to Parliament said there was evidence to suggest that Novartis made payments to politicians.
docs.lead_paragraph: ATHENS — After 20 hours of acrimonious debate, Greek lawmakers on Thursday approved the formation of a parliamentary committee to investigate accusations linking 10 high-profile politicians to bribery by a Swiss drug manufacturer.

headline.main: Greece Approves Bribery Investigation Involving Political Elite
headline.print_headline: Did Novartis Bribe 10 Politicians? Greece Approves an Investigation

docs.abstract: Uber abruptly sold its ride-hailing operations to its top competitor, creating a virtual monopoly in the region and daring regulators to stop it.
docs.snippet: Uber abruptly sold its ride-hailing operations to its top competitor, creating a virtual monopoly in the region and daring regulators to stop it.
docs.lead_paragraph: MUMBAI, India — In a new television ad, Uber’s chief executive, Dara Khosrowshahi, pledges to move the ride-hailing giant beyond its bad-boy past. “One of our core values as a company is to always do the right thing,” declares Mr. Khosrowshahi, who joined the business nine months ago.

headline.main: Uber’s Exit From Southeast Asia Upsets Regulators and Drivers
headline.print_headline: Uber’s Exit Leaves Asia In an Uproar
